rply to 1993, 40%</li>\n<li>Falls sharply to 2003, 23%</li>\n<li>Falls gradually to 2013, 17%</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 2023, 18%</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The Senate line:&nbsp;<br/>\n<ul>\n<li>Begins at 1953, 74%</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1973, 79%</li>\n<li>Falls sharply to 1993, 63%</li>\n<li>Falls sharply to 2003, 35%</li>\n<li>Falls sharply to 2013, 18%</li>\n<li>Falls gradually to 2023, 17%</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Since the nation&rsquo;s earliest days, both houses of the United States Congress have counted many military veterans among their elected officials, including Hiram <span data-ssml-sub-alias=\"L\">L.</span> Fong (who served in the US Army Air Force) and Ralph Harold Metcalfe <span data-ssml-sub-alias=\"Sr\">Sr.</span> (who served in the US Army). A research institute gathered historical data about congressional members who have reported past military experience and determined that <span aria-hidden=\"true\">______</span><span class=\"sr-only\">blank</span></p>"
